<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-12-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-12-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="10" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d10">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 1012/7–8.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Sands</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-12-06"><hi rend="italic">December 6,
                                1907</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 42.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to transmit a letter or
                            petition addressed by several Chinese merchants in good standing in this
                            community to the <pb facs="0744" n="594" xml:id="pg_594"/> Chinese
                            minister to the United States on the subject of the recent rigorous
                            application of the exclusion laws of this Republic to the Chinese
                            race.</p>
                        <p>I shall report fully to the department upon this subject by the next
                            mail.</p>
                        <p>The action taken by the Chinese in this matter has been by my advice.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">W. F. Sands.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>